question.title: Can someone shed some light on this ANR log?

node.contents: what are you doing in UpdateMovieService.java:179 onstart() . Post the code. Are you trying to concurrently modifying a file from threads?

astNode.text: what are you doing in UpdateMovieService.java:179 onstart() . Post the code. Are you trying to concurrently modifying a file from threads?

node.contents: It's simply checking if the file exists in that line. And no, it's only doing something to one file at a time. However, I do have a theory. Could this be caused by my service running in the background while the user tries to interact with the file in question?

node.contents: Just a note so no one gets confused reading this: It's not accessing a Service's functions for more than 5 seconds it's the onstart/oncreate/etc service lifecycle calls that happen on the main thread highlighted here: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/10679315/how-to-avoid-anr-in-standalone-android-service

node.contents: It seems that the ANR was caused by the Service running for more than 5 seconds. Apparently a few users had a very large number of files that it had to go through. I've solved it by moving all the hard work to an AsyncTask.
